data.description:
The `publish-subscribe` pattern is one that allows communication between two or more things (modules, functions, etc.) without having them be tightly coupled.  In this pattern, the communication happens through a `hub` over channels (`topics`), which are generally identified by a string.  When a user wants to `subscribe` to a topic, they will provide a function (`handler`) that will be executed when the topic is published.  When a user wants to `publish` a topic, they will need only call the hub's `publish` method, indicating the topic identifier, and passing in any other relevant information as additional arguments.

Create a pub/sub system that allows a user to:

* Subscribe to a topic
* Publish to a topic

When a user publishes to a topic, any arguments provided to the `publish` method, not including the `topic`, should be passed to the handler(s).

```javascript
var handle = hub.subscribe("user/added", function (user) {
  console.log("A user named " + user.name + " was added!");
});

var user = {
  name: "Matt"
};

users.add(user);

hub.publish("user/added", user); // logs "A user named Matt was added!"
```


When a user subscribes to a topic, the subscription method should return an object (`handle`) that has a `remove` method on it.  That method should remove that subscription.  If there are multiple handles subscribed to a topic and a handle's `remove` method is called, only that handle's subscription should be removed.  All other handles should operate as normal.

```javascript
var handle = hub.subscribe("test/remove", function () {
  console.log("Testing handle");
});

hub.publish("test/remove"); // Testing handle

handle.remove();

hub.publish("test/remove"); // Nothing is logged
```
